Histogram of Users Birthdays

#install.packages('ggplot2')
library(ggplot2)
qplot(x=dob_day, data=pf) + scale_x_discrete(breaks=1:31)

What are some things that you notice about this histogram?

Response: There are many more people born on the 1st of the month. I would expect that the number of people born on each day of the month to be about the same, except the 31st since only a few months have 31 days.

Faceting

qplot(x=dob_day, data=pf, binwidth=1) + facet_wrap(~dob_month, ncol=4)

Lets take another look at our plot. What stands out to you here?

Response: There are many many more people born on January 1 than any other day of the year. ***

Be Skeptical - Outliers and Anomalies

Notes: The large numbers on January 1 could be an error or users defaulting to January 1 for privacy.

Friend Count

What code would you enter to create a histogram of friend counts?

qplot(x=friend_count, data = pf)
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

Limiting the Axes

qplot(x=friend_count, data = pf) + scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0,1000))
## stat_bin: binwidth defaulted to range/30. Use 'binwidth = x' to adjust this.

Faceting Friend Count

What code would you add to create a facet the histogram by gender?

qplot(x = friend_count, data = pf, binwidth = 10) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000),
                     breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) + facet_wrap(~gender)

Omitting NA Values

qplot(x = friend_count, data = subset(pf, !is.na(gender)), binwidth = 10) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(0, 1000),
                     breaks = seq(0, 1000, 50)) + facet_wrap(~gender)

Who on average has more friends: men or women?

Response: Women #### Whats the difference between the median friend count for women and men? Response: 22 #### Why would the median be a better measure than the mean? Response: There are some people with many more or far fewer friends than the majority of the group, which can skew the mean if they are not balanced. The median is more robust to individual responses. ***

Tenure

qplot(x=tenure, data=pf, binwidth = 30, color = I('black'), fill = I('#099DD9'))

How would you create a histogram of tenure by year?

qplot(x=tenure/365, data=pf, binwidth = .25, color = I('black'), fill = I('#099DD9'))

Labeling Plots

qplot(x=tenure/365, data=pf, binwidth = .25, color = I('black'), fill = I('#F79420')) + xlab('Number of years using Facebook') + ylab('Number of users in sample') + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(1, 7, 1), limits = c(0,7))

User Ages

qplot(x=age, data=pf, binwidth = 1, color = I('black'), fill = I('#5760AB')) + xlab('Ages of users in sample') + ylab('Number of users in sample') + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, 120, 20), limits = c(10,125))

What do you notice?

Response: There are some spikes in ages > 100 ***

Getting Logical
